April 11, 2025

The walk commenced around 10:00 AM and concluded roughly thirty minutes later. The weather was overcast.

The initial portion of the walk started near the Canadian Museum of Nature. The museum is sometimes referred to as "The Castle" due to its resemblance to medieval fortresses, the result of extensive work and use of limestone. The colour of the entrance was grey stone.

The route then progressed in a southeasterly direction toward Elgin Street. The portion of the walk was at a steady pace. Elgin street has a multitude of restaurants. It has undergone several transformations, from a residential area to the vibrant street it is today, making it one of Ottawa's most prominent thoroughfares.

Continuing southeast, the path led close to Confederation Park. The park is home to the National War Memorial. The pace slowed down during this section of the walk. The park has a distinctive green hue. The park is renowned for hosting various events, including the Ottawa International Jazz Festival.

The path then curved towards the Rideau Canal. During this portion of the walk it curved northeast. The canal is an engineering marvel that has served as a vital waterway for centuries. Its waters were a deep blue.

Finally, the route led back in a northwesterly direction along a portion of the canal, concluding the walk. The path lead near the Lord Elgin hotel which looks like a castle. It is named after James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin, a former Governor General of Canada. The pace of the path picked up at the end. The buildings nearby reflected many colours of the sky.
